x4freetext: . The Relative Uncertainty.
* by Authors *
In the Case of Ni-60,  Because  of  a  Wrinkle  in  the
Target  and  the  Subsequent  Uncertainty in the Target
Thickness, a Somewhat Arbitrary  Normalization  of  the
Cross-Section  Data was Made.  After the Nominal Target
Thickness was Included, All the Data were Normalized by
A  Factor of 1.1.  This was done to Make the Ni-60 Data
Consistent with the Ni-58 and Ni-62 Data, and was  Felt
To  be a Safe Procedure Since Such Consistency has Been
Shown in the Data of Robertson and Funsten at 17.5  MeV
Proton Scattering.

.Absolute Uncertainty.

Is Felt to be About 10% For the 2+ States and About 20%
For the 3- States, Because of the Uncertainty in the
Experimental Points and the Extrapolation of the Fitted
Curves to 0 Ang. Degree and 180 Degree.
